<!-- DescriptionListGroup -->
<details>
  <summary>📝 DescriptionListGroup Wrapping</summary>
  <div class="details-content">
    <h4>What changed in PF6</h4>
    <p>In PF6, <code>DescriptionList</code> children should be wrapped in <code>&lt;DescriptionListGroup&gt;</code>. The main branch already uses this pattern extensively (89 references), but Branch 2 adds it to additional detail sections that were missing it.</p>

    <h4>Branch 2</h4>
    <p>Added ~85 new <code>DescriptionListGroup</code> references wrapping DetailsItem components in various detail sections (DetailsSection, CredentialsSection, SecretsSection, etc.).</p>

    <h4>Assessment</h4>
    <p>This is a <strong>correct PF6 pattern</strong> — DescriptionListGroup is the proper wrapper for description list term/description pairs. However, many of the wrapped components (e.g., <code>NameDetailsItem</code>, <code>NamespaceDetailsItem</code>) may already render their own DescriptionListGroup internally, which could cause double-wrapping. Without runtime verification, this is uncertain.</p>

    <p><strong>Winner: <span class="badge badge-orange">Branch 2</span></strong> — likely correct but carries risk of double-wrapping.</p>
  </div>
</details>

<!-- CRITICAL: component= prop misuse -->
<details open>
  <summary>🚨 CRITICAL: StackItem/SplitItem component= Prop Misuse (Branch 2)</summary>
  <div class="details-content">
    <h4>The Problem</h4>
    <p>Branch 2 systematically moves children content (text strings, JSX elements) from being <em>children</em> of <code>&lt;StackItem&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;SplitItem&gt;</code> into their <code>component=</code> prop. <strong>This is semantically wrong.</strong></p>
    <p>The <code>component</code> prop on PatternFly layout components specifies the <strong>HTML element type</strong> to render (e.g., <code>"div"</code>, <code>"span"</code>, <code>"li"</code>). It does NOT accept content/children.</p>

    <h4>Examples of the bug (~88 instances)</h4>
    <pre><code>// BEFORE (main — correct)
&lt;StackItem className="text-muted"&gt;
  {t('Rules with "Preferred" condition will stack with an "AND" relation between them.')}
&lt;/StackItem&gt;

// AFTER (Branch 2 — BROKEN)
&lt;StackItem className="text-muted"
  component={t('Rules with "Preferred" condition will stack with an "AND" relation between them.')} /&gt;</code></pre>

    <pre><code>// BEFORE (main — correct)
&lt;StackItem&gt;
  {t('Defines the CPU limits allocated to the main container...')}
&lt;/StackItem&gt;

// AFTER (Branch 2 — BROKEN)
&lt;StackItem component={t('Defines the CPU limits allocated to the main container...')} /&gt;</code></pre>

    <h4>Impact</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><span class="badge badge-red">UI Text Disappears</span> — The text content that was previously rendered as children will no longer appear. Instead, React will try to use the text string as an HTML element type, which will either render an empty unknown element or throw a runtime error.</li>
      <li><span class="badge badge-red">~88 affected locations</span> across help content components, description texts, project select fields, settings help content, storage product fields, and more.</li>
      <li>This is the <strong>single biggest reason Branch 2 cannot be merged</strong>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Root Cause</h4>
    <p>This appears to be an AI agent's misunderstanding of what the <code>component</code> prop does. The agent likely saw PatternFly migration guidance about "moving content to props" (which applies to things like EmptyState's titleText prop or Button's icon prop) and over-applied the pattern to layout components where it doesn't apply.</p>

    <p><strong>Winner: <span class="badge badge-green">Branch 1</span></strong> — does not have this issue.</p>
  </div>
</details>

